---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Luminosity function";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Luminosity function</h1>

    <p>
      A <strong>luminosity function (LF)</strong> describes the number density of objects (e.g., stars, galaxies) as a function of luminosity or absolute magnitude. For stellar populations it is a fundamental diagnostic used to infer the underlying mass function, evolutionary states, and integrated light of systems.
    </p>

    <h2>Applications</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Convert star counts into mass functions.</li>
      <li>Estimate integrated luminosity and stellar mass of galactic components.</li>
      <li>Compare populations across environments (disk vs halo).</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example measurement</h2>
    <p>
      <a href="/pages/bird_2026_galactic_stellar_halo_lf">Bird et al. (2026)</a> present a continuous measurement of the Milky Way stellar halo LF from M_G ≈ 13 to M_G ≈ -3 using Gaia DR3.
    </p>

    <h2>See also</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/stellar_halo" text="Stellar halo" /></li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/color-magnitude_diagram" text="Color–magnitude diagram" /></li>
    </ul>
  </main>
</Base>
